english:
  title: 'Epitaph and Preface for the Tomb of Lord Mun-sun, Posthumously Honored: Guardian of the Great Protector, Chamberlain of the Palace Gate, Grand Counselor, Academician of the Hall of Cultivated Literature, Supervisor of the Compilation of the National History, Minister of Rites, and Academician of the Forest of Scholars'
  author: Lee Su
  language: eng
  text: "The Lord bore the family name Lee, personal name Kyubō, courtesy name Chunkyŏng. He was from Hwangnyŏ County. His father, whose name was Yunnyu, served as Minister of the Department of Households. His mother, Lady Kim of Kumyang County, was honored as Lady of the Golden Orchid Commandery through his station—the daughter of Siyŏng, Magistrate of Ujin County.\n\nAt nine years of age, the Lord could already compose prose. By fifteen or sixteen, he had acquired vast learning and a prodigious memory. In whatever he wrote, he never merely echoed the stale words of the ancients. Throughout his life he called himself \"Tang Paeksa,\" and men of his time pointed at him, saying, \"The flying brush of Li Tang-paeksa.\"\n\nIn the year Kiyu, under the patronage of the renowned Chancellor Yuk Kongkwŏn, he placed first in the examination for the Office of the Grand Commandant. The following year he presented himself for the provincial examination in three sessions. On the examination day, the examiners, respecting his reputation, pressed him to drink several cups of the imperial wine. Growing somewhat intoxicated, his writing lost its refinement, and his score was consequently modest. He wished to decline and try again, but his stern father rebuked him severely, and lacking precedent for such withdrawal, he could not refuse. To congratulating visitors he said, \"Though my rank be humble, is this not the work of one tested three or four times?\"  \n\nIn the year Chŏngsa, the Great Censor Cho Yŏngin and three other learned chancellors jointly submitted a memorial recommending him to the throne. But the memorial fell into the hands of envious men and was suppressed. Ten years after receiving his degree, he was appointed Assistant Magistrate of Chŏnju, where he repeatedly checked the unlawful conduct of the Deputy Administrator. For this he was impeached and dismissed. Later, when scholars of the Forest of Scholars recommended candidates, the Lord was always placed first among them. Thus in the year Chŏngmyo he was given a concurrent post in the Forest of Scholars, becoming confirmed there the following year.\n\nIn the first month of the year Imsin, he was appointed Recorder-Administrator of the Thousand-Bull Guard and left the Academy. In the sixth month, holding the concurrent title of Exemplary Scholar, he returned to the Academy. In the twelfth month, without passing through the seventh rank, he became Vice-Minister of Court Provisions while retaining his Academy post. In the year Ŭlhae, he was appointed Right Remonstrator, and later served as Left and Right Inspector-General. In the year Kimyo, he went out as Vice-Administrator of Kye-yang Prefecture, serving one year. He was then recalled as Court Gentleman of the Department of Rites and Chronicler. After this he held the positions of Junior Director of the Imperial Stud, Waiting Scholar of the Precious Text Pavilion, Director of the Office of Public Works, Lecturer of the National Academy, and Attendant Lecturer of the Forest of Scholars, and Controller of the Office of Court Ritual. In nine years his promotions were thus achieved.\n\nIn the year Kyŏngin, through a grave misfortune, he was exiled to Hedgehog Island. At that time three others received the same banishment—all were upright officials of renown. In the year Sinmyo, he received amnesty and returned to the capital. At this time the Mongols invaded, and the Lord, holding only a nominal post, undertook all the diplomatic correspondence. In the fourth month of the year Imjin, he was appointed Counselor of Rectitude, Minister of the Ministry of Secrets, Scholar of the Precious Text Pavilion, and Keeper of the Heir Apparent's Palace. From the time he entered the council until this appointment, except for one year serving in the provinces, he continuously held responsibility for the imperial decrees.\n\nIn the sixth month of the year Kyesa, he was appointed Brilliant Purple Palace Attendant, Vice-Minister of the Imperial Chancellery, Right Attendant at the Gate, and Scholar of the Precious Text Pavilion. In the twelfth month he entered the chief council as Grand Purple Palace Attendant, Minister of the Gate, Minister of Household Revenues, Academician of the Hall of Collected Worthies, and Minister of Rites. In the twelfth month of the year Ŭlmi, he became Vice-Premier, Academician of the Hall of Cultivated Literature, Minister of Household Affairs, and Grand Protector of the Heir Apparent. In the tenth month he submitted a memorial requesting retirement. The throne sent ministers of close counsel to persuade him to stay, but the Lord, having no choice, returned to his duties. Yet again he pressed his request for retirement with increasing earnestness. Unable to deny his wishes, the throne allowed him to retire as Guardian of the Great Protector, Chamberlain of the Palace Gate, Grand Counselor, Academician of the Hall of Cultivated Literature, Supervisor of the National History, Minister of Rites, Academician of the Forest of Scholars, and Grand Protector of the Heir Apparent.\n\nOnce he presided over the examination of the National Academy, and three times opened the examinations for the Department of Rites. The scholars he selected were many who excelled in poetry and letters. Upon leaving office, he amused himself with poetry and wine, and devoted himself to reading the Surangama Sutra, the eulogy of which appears in the ninth volume of his collected works. He also composed numerous imperial rescripts and diplomatic correspondence with foreign courts, leaving nothing undone.\n\nIn the seventh month of the year Sinchuk, he fell slightly ill. The great ministers then in power sent distinguished physicians to attend him. They took up the Lord's collected works and had them engraved, hoping he would see them published before his eyes. Though the work was grand, it remained unfinished. On the second day of the ninth month, he passed away at his private residence, at the age of seventy-four. The throne mourned him greatly, commanding the officials to gather for his funeral and conferring upon him the posthumous name Lord of Refined Harmony.\n\nAlas! Though I have already enumerated the progression of the Lord's offices and ranks, how can I omit the traces of those auspicious signs and deeds that marked his life? When the Lord was but a few months old, foul sores covered his entire body, his face all ulcerated. His wet-nurse, seeing this, carried him outside and placed him at the gate. An old man passed by, gazed upon him, and said, \"Can this child be reckoned in mere gold? He must be carefully nurtured.\" The nurse ran back to tell his father, who, suspecting this was a divine being, hurried after him but could not overtake him. Thus was the Lord protected by a spirit in his swaddling.\n\nWhen the Lord prepared to take the examination of the Grand Commandant, he dreamed he saw men dressed in finely beaten black silk gathered in a hall, drinking wine. Those beside him said, \"These are the Twenty-Eight Lodges of Heaven.\" The Lord, startled and reverent, prostrated himself twice and asked whether he would succeed in the examination that year. One of them pointed to another and said, \"That one is the Quai Star. Go and ask him.\" The Lord approached and questioned him, but before hearing the response, he awoke. Soon he dreamed again, and the same man came to tell him, \"You shall surely place first. This is Heaven's decree—reveal it to no one.\" His former name had been Yinnjo, and now he changed it to Kyubō. When he took the examination, he indeed placed first. Thus did the celestial luminary guard the Lord within the sphere of learning.\n\nIn the year Imsul, rebellion broke out in the Eastern Capital. Three armies were sent to suppress it. Among the military, they sought to select from those of nominally lower ranks who had passed the examinations to serve as commissioners. But war is perilous, and all sought to avoid it through cunning. The Lord alone stood forth and said, \"Though I am timid and fearful, to shrink from the nation's trial is not to be human.\" Thus he marched with the army. This was the Lord's courage in righteousness.\n\nIn the year Mugin, at the Eightfold Assembly, the Lord attended an imperial banquet. The ceremony had not yet reached its midpoint when a certain chancellor urged its premature conclusion. The Lord said, \"This is the throne's gift and cannot be dismissed so summarily.\" Though he suffered banishment for this stand, it showed how the Lord upheld the law without wavering. \n\nThose Mongols, stubborn as beasts, neither respond to the celestial music of the spheres nor to gifts of the rarest pearls and jade. Yet when they heard of the Lord's words and intentions, they were moved to compassion, and all his proposals they followed. Thus did the Lord's sincerity move even the unmoved.\n\nHe took as wife the second daughter of the Grand Commandant Chin Sŭng, by whom he had four sons and two daughters. The eldest, Kwan, died before the Lord. Ham now serves as Vice-Administrator of Hongju. Ch'ŏng serves as Clerk of the Kyŏngsŏn Temple, and Che as Clerk of the Western Great Compassion Temple. The eldest daughter married Li Yushin, Inner Attendant and Keeper of the Palace Gate, and the second married Koh Paekcham, Clerk of the Kyŏnghŭi Palace.\n\nAh! The composing of epitaphs is an ancient art. Only when one's achievements shine forth and command the world's esteem is such a record made, so that posterity may know that among the ages there appeared a man of uncommon greatness. Yet though such a man be truly uncommon, if the epitaph falls to an unworthy pen, better that it were never written. Though my own hand is clumsy at writing, the Lord would say to me in his leisure hours, \"When I am gone, write my epitaph.\" His successor Ham, speaking for the Lord, came to me with this request. Reluctant but unable to refuse, I compose this epitaph:\n\n*From the Chiang to the Fen flows wisdom,*\n*In Eastern seas, a sage to rival Kong-fu-tze.*\n*Warm and upright, respectful and frugal,*\n*In life, honor; in death, lamentation.*\n\n*Before seventy,*\n*A worthy man of his age,*\n*Who carved the Record in Jade Hall—*\n*Small tasks for the Lord.*\n*Turning the cosmic breath,*\n*This was his station.*\n\n*After seventy,*\n*Heaven claimed him then.*\n*Men's longing knew no bound,*\n*Yet Heaven took him soon.*\n*Heaven seized his vital force,*\n*Earth holds his earthly form—*\n*How can they be but two?*\n*In heaven and on earth,*\n*The man fades from sight.*\n*What remains are his words,*\n*Yet I fear the spirits of thunder*\n*And lightning may bear them away.*\n\n*I gather craftsmen here,*\n*And carve them upon stone,*\n*That the great mirror fades not.*\n*The Son of Heaven, compassionate,*\n*Commanded the officials:*\n*Beside the sacred mountain*\n*Plant his tomb.*\n*The plains stretch open,*\n*The peaks rise high.*\n*Since the mountain itself is spiritual,*\n*May his descendants flourish*\n*For ten thousand generations.*"
  footnotes:
    - Tang Paeksa (唐白) references Li Taibai, the famous Tang dynasty poet Li Bo, indicating the Lord's reputation as an exceptional writer whose style flowed naturally like the master's brush.
    - The Twenty-Eight Lodges (二十八宿) refer to the lunar mansions of Chinese astronomy. The Quai Star (奎星) is the constellation associated with literary achievement and scholarship.
    - The Eightfold Assembly (八關會) was a major court ceremony during the Goryeo period where officials gathered for official functions and banquets.
    - The Surangama Sutra (楞嚴經) is an important Buddhist scripture; the Lord's devotion to it in his retirement years reflects his spiritual depth beyond mere statecraft.
    - The epitaph's final section employs the classical literary device of imagining the subject's spiritual journey and legacy, as was customary in Korean funerary inscriptions.
